CatDescriptText: Miss Jimmee Brown, unemployed, 7624 Tioga Street and Mrs. Betty Gondek, housewife, 801 Steiner Street, were part of the "Pittsburghers Speak Up" column published in the Pittsburgh Courier Newspaper December 19, 1959, pg. A1 with question: "Do you think that President Eisenhower is as popular today as he was when he first was when he first took office?  Why?  Do you think that the fact that he is not running for office will influence the election?" Miss Jimmee Brown's answer reads: "Not as popular.  He didn't carry out certain things the people expected.  I can't say much about the coming election."  Mrs. Betty Gondek's answer reads: "I think he is as popular.  I know he is with me...I like him and it is not because of politics...I don't know about the coming election."
TitMainTitle: Two frames: Portrait of Jimmee Brown wearing textured button down coat, eyeglasses, head scarf, and dark gloves, holding dark handbag, standing on Wood Street across from Dimlings Candy, Downtown; Portrait of Betty Gondek wearing textured coat with rounded collar and single round button at neckline and light colored gloves and hat, standing on Wood Street across from General Office Equipment, Downtown
